#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #1      keep it stupid simple, dont use cryptic names or unnecessary "obfuscating" code. If code needs to  be                                                                                            â”‹
#â”‹         obfuscated, you can convert it to a binary file and use something akin to pklite or encrypt it, there are                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹         many many other ways, but if its open source. DONT OBFUSCATE, it will just lead to someone elses headache                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹         later. Who knows maybe saving the world will rely on your code, do you really want the world to blow up because                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹         you wanted your code to look cool? Remember, If its not needed, it probably isn't.                                                                                                               â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #2      using linux? use tputs, its compatible with just about everything, and, its CORE. which means theres a 99.5% chance                                                                              â”‹
#â”‹         whatever linux client will have some form of tputs available. From there, fail back to standard ansi/vt terminal                                                                                 â”‹
#â”‹         control sequences or just plain clear text. (linux the OS, not linux the terminal var (TERM=linux) read on for that one-v)                                                                       â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #3      Graphics are all or nothing, if in terminology we use tyls/tycat, if not we dont                                                                                                                 â”‹
#â”‹         If we are in X11, its 2020 so its safe to use Unicode at this point, its universal! Besides, everyone else uses it                                                                               â”‹
#â”‹         now too, so we can get often used graphics from it. And it falls back so dont be shy, if your current font doesnt                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹         have the 8-ball, it will fall back to the core font that does. And there is always a core font that has all the symbols                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹         (unless we are talking about other-region language chars, dont mess with them unless you want to get really messy!).                                                                             â”‹
#â”‹         and on that note...                                                                                                                                                                              â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #4      Translations should be done transparently. Use a wrapper to achieve this, dont modify the original code. This ensures future                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹         updates will also work, dependencies should not translate, their owner/parent SHOULD. For CLI programs, its best to either xlat                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹         on the fly or use a wrapper of some sort. No extra files should be created, use shm instead of tmp, etc, etc.                                                                                    â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #5      Dont be afraid to strip down the comments, many times things will get bloated with nonsense or out of date material, lets keep it simple                                                         â”‹
#â”‹         just like #1 says.                                                                                                                                                                               â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #6      Subs that are called by other subs are considered internal, unless recursive. Subs that get called directly from Main:: are considered                                                           â”‹
#â”‹         to be "main" or "global" subroutines. Internal functions must be separated, and should be no more than a few lines long and deep*.                                                               â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹         * deep meaning indent level or loop depth (ie; if { while { given { <loop depth is 3 here> } } else { <depth is only 1 here> } <and zero here>)                                                  â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”£â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”«                                                                                                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹ CSCS2020 COMPLIANT COMMENTS / EMBEDDED NOTES (I know, they start at 11 instead of 1, but i dont like to do things the normal way)                                                                        â”‹
#â”£â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”«                                                                                                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹ #11-a  special feature: arguments that are prefixxed with + (ie, like +-A) will seek out any matching arg                                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹ #11-f  special precheck: find if user specifically set column widths or column counts (but not both!)                                                                                                    â”‹
#â”‹ #11    warning, because of ls(1) behavior, we must also follow symlinks realpaths not the physical one the user sees                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹         so if you are in /somedir thats a link to /usr/share, ../tmp will not work, you would need to use ../../tmp!                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹         only not considering paths that are absolute as compound paths                                                                                                                                   â”‹
#â”‹ #12     first form, single color to setaf/b                                                                                                                                                              â”‹
#â”‹         second form, non-standard term control code (see google:terminal-24bit-color-ansi-sequences for details)                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹ #13     direct is for the 24-bit standalone control codes (separate from regular sequences). tput does not document                                                                                      â”‹
#â”‹         a way to pass this through requiring it to be done manually. Additionally, 24-bit support is not included in                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹         termcap/terminfo, so user must decide to enable it themselves.                                                                                                                                   â”‹
#â”‹ #14     1) columnizing output is a work in progress, and has not been completed some variables that are being used at the moment are:                                                                    â”‹
#â”‹         colpos    which column are we in, defaults to 0.                                                                                                                                                 â”‹
#â”‹         colwidth  width of each individual cell defaults to 32.                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹         maxpos    max before resetting, changed by termcap's column entry, defaults to 4.                                                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹         2) columnar sizing depends on filename lengths, actual columns, user preferences and so-on, it is by far not close to being complete (but is functional).                                        â”‹
#â”‹ #15     The colorize code is checked for three basic forms, the most common is ~f[f[f]] which is just a ~0 - ~256, next check is                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹         ~fffbbb compact code form (warning, no check for > 256 here is done, its on the programmer to use this properly!)                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹         After that, the ~ffbb compact code form (preferred, though limited to 0-99 it is guarenteed to not be out of range), and then                                                                    â”‹
#â”‹         anything else used like ~9999994 is not valid, values are expected to be base 10 integers at this time but may incur changes as rgb support is added.                                            â”‹
#â”‹         after all codes are validated its value is inserted (padding with zeros is ok and suggested for above f and b codes)                                                                             â”‹
#â”‹ #16     finalent: where the final text is rendered just before it is printed file, kind: filetype text is rendered here                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #17    Use $colors < next_color_count to calculate number of colors (this would catch odd color counts and rounds them down), possibly add those counts when encountered                                 â”‹
#â”‹        In 99% of the cases, user will have either 256 colors, or 16 colors. (in a /dev/tty? or a /dev/pt*, respectively )                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #18   color tables, instead of hardcoding colors for bits, each bit translates to an appropriate palette color                                                                                           â”‹
#â”‹       based on desired type; each entry defined as a list of entries, name pattern is @col_xlat_tab[kind]                                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹       where [kind] is one of:                                                                                                                                                                            â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹           16      Generic 16 color palette (8 in hardware terminal fallback mode)                                                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹                   terminals with 8 colors will have the bright attribute removed                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹                   terminals with no color will be stripped entirely.                                                                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹           256     Generic 256 color palette, using direct preprogrammed indexes                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹                   terminals with 88 colors will be hue-matched by terminal itself                                                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹           rgb     Also 256 colors, but accesses the colors using R/G/B values, still                                                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹                   only from the color cube preprogrammed into the terminal.                                                                                                                              â”‹
#â”‹           true    True color mode (24-bit), 16 million colors, with an unlimited                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹                   number of pairs, approximated to 256->16->none if terminal doesnt                                                                                                                      â”‹
#â”‹                   support it. (See above for info about limitations on truecolor support)                                                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹       The user can set these values in the code however a .lsrc is planned for later                                                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹       tying colortable to 'dircolors' and its file(s).                                                                                                                                                   â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #19   Default is 6, during an in-depth test of this, never did see any field larger than 6                                                                                                               â”‹
#â”‹       The normal value to see is 2-4 with occasional 5, 6 only came up in /dev or other                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹       special folders (esp hybrid).                                                                                                                                                                      â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #20   regex (qr//) patterns precompiled using interpolated strings will be used for both;                                                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹       the first pass is for data interpolation, the second assignment closures the first                                                                                                                 â”‹
#â”‹       and redefines it as a compiled pattern (via qr//) preventing too many single use                                                                                                                   â”‹
#â”‹       variables from piiling up.                                                                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #21    use Term::ANSIColor:                                                                                                                                                                              â”‹
