#â”‹ #26 added ANSI0 thru ANSI255 constants as constants only, since constants dont actually take up memory (they are not allocated, just are replaced inline, and are not even looked at if they arent used aâ”‹
#â”‹     this is also to counter any usage of Term::ANSIColor that may have been used, preventing it integration since it basically ignores normal terminal preferences                                       â”‹
#â”‹     and spews incorrect color codes for any terminal other than ANSI-specific ones like linux and xterm. It is so unportable its not even funny.                                                         â”‹
#â”‹ #27 in reference to "sub filecolor":                                                                                                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹      At the moment, filecolor represents two things:                                                                                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹        - the file's 'size group' (as seen in the legend, which is also calculated here)                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹        - the file's ownership (usually group ownership)                                                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹      Ownership is applied to the background color, if the file does not belong to the current user                                                                                                       â”‹
#â”‹      Size groups are applied to the foreground color, a file can be only in one size group.                                                                                                              â”‹
#â”‹        There are two special size groups, empty (<1), and infinitely large (>LSB)                                                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹        The rest of the size groups fall into the range of ( >A && <B ) Group A is the "minimum" size for an item in a size group, group B is                                                             â”‹
#â”‹          the "maximum" size in that same group. "infinitely large" is calculated using the largest size in group B (LSB).                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹        Directories size groups are calculated not by the size of the directory entry (which is always the same, so its useless to show that                                                              â”‹
#â”‹          over and over), but by the total size of the items WITHIN that directory (controlled by the recursion and maxdepth options TBA).                                                                â”‹
#â”‹        Symbolic links reflect the sizes of the items for which they represent. Hard links are treated as regular files since technically all                                                             â”‹
#â”‹        regular files are also hardlinks (hardlinks with an refcount of 1, or 2 with '.' and '..'). Other than the pedantics given above, and                                                             â”‹
#â”‹        the legend, no additional information regarding sizes are given.                                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹      In reference to "$fallbackcolor" and the rest of the lists, color numbers are for map, not actual color numbers                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹      The trucolormap cannot be implemented until the last few terminals embrance the new trucolor terminal standard (there are 3 major brands                                                            â”‹
#â”‹        that refuse to do this, you know who you are *cough*erminolog..rxv..kon*cough*) the locolormap is an approxmation for @colormap, if you                                                           â”‹
#â”‹        change it try to keep the codes simmilar so they make sense to the user when switching from hicolor to locolor environments, this will                                                            â”‹
#â”‹        be conversely true for truecolor maps when/if they are implemented in reference to $size:                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹           - files                                                                                                                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹               count bytes (file) or target bytes (symlink)                                                                                                                                               â”‹
#â”‹           - dirs                                                                                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹               count total bytes within branch (dir) or link target branch (symlink-dir)                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #28 in reference to the colormaps (for filecolors)                                                                                                                                                       â”‹
#â”‹     There is probably the question, why is a color map needed when approximation could be precalculated?                                                                                                 â”‹
#â”‹      Two reasons:                                                                                                                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹           1 - Precalculated is faster,   2 - Explicit Approximation is faster                                                                                                                            â”‹
#â”‹      In the future, if requested, the tables would be precalculated on first run, and written into a configuration file. Once the File::Config module                                                    â”‹
#â”‹      is completed that might be the case. As with most of my esoteric projects, especially perl ones, this is also a grounds for developing modules                                                      â”‹
#â”‹      in their native environment, so that will come first.                                                                                                                                               â”‹
#â”‹    additionally:                                                                                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹      note that there should never be (initially) more than 15 size range colors, this will ensure that low color terminals arent having to process a bunch                                               â”‹
#â”‹      of numbers that dont even matter. This is another thing that would change later (the how, not the why).                                                                                             â”‹
#â”‹   ADDED                                                                                                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹      new constants, "INF" which is the stand-in for the same old special -1 which basically mean infinity- when in 'min' and infinity+ when in 'max'                                                     â”‹
#â”‹      the not so familiar "AUTO" constant which is a new special value -2, which means to automatically calculate the minimum based on the last maximum                                                   â”‹
#â”‹      value, this special value can only be used in the 'min' column, it has no special meaning in the 'max' column. I was going to add support for the                                                   â”‹
#â”‹      max column too, but it would make the process twice as slow and I couldnt see any real gain other than switching columns. The main gain here is                                                     â”‹
#â”‹      that you can now just specify a single number (like in a gradient) instead of figuring out the range, which is much easier to change also.                                                          â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #29 in reference to count_in_dir's depth and what parameters: both use INF but for very different reasons                                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹     entirely, so:                                                                                                                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #30 option addition has already been done, but should not be printed unless --help was not issued                                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹ #31 during initial testing, files checked and otherwise neither are directories and go on to below items, has been rewritten to happen at the END of dosort instead                                      â”‹
#â”‹  |  for further regrouping, as covered below in 31-a. The regular sorting is done first so that regrouping will have files sorted within their own groups                                                â”‹
#â”‹  |  prior to being regrouped.                                                                                                                                                                            â”‹
#â”‹  |                                                                                                                                                                                                       â”‹
#â”‹  +-- 31-a)    sorting links first with -2 causes them to be sandwiched when -0 is used, between dirs and files                                                                                           â”‹
#â”‹               when -0 is used, linked directories go before plain links but after nonlinked directories (creating 4 differing groups;                                                                    â”‹
#â”‹               1-physical dirs, 2-linked dirs, 3-linked files, 4-physical files, each sorted within depending on --sort, to their own group.                                                              â”‹
#â”‹ #32 @toadd is needed because @ARGV is the target and the source for examination. Adding items into @ARGV while checking within @ARGV causes the                                                          â”‹
#â”‹     examiner to get false positives (items it added or did not add yet), for this reason, @toadd was needed to buffer the items until the operation                                                      â”‹
#â”‹     has completed, then it is added in after the fact. TODO: add some sort of security sanitizing of the environment variables before they are put in                                                    â”‹
#â”‹     attotw it does not have access to system, qx, fork, or exec, ``, etc so its not a priority.                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ #33 sz, szw, added because i wanted them, may later add a switch to enable/disable them, but for now 12 digits is ok                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹              (fyi 12 digits = xxx,xxx,xxx,xxx which is 0.9 TB filesize max will be visible, which is ok for now, larger will be chopped                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹               servers and people with beefy machines can change this to 15 or 18, but beyond 18 (999 PB!) wont be needed in the near future for desktop users                                            â”‹
#â”‹               (near 2021), clusters, forests, datacenters, may need 21 or 24 by mid 2025, but you can change it so go ahead...open source!                                                               â”‹
#â”‹ #34 given, when using given anywhere, must pass a copy unless we want our variable to be changed when some other inner method/function uses $_!                                                          â”‹
#â”‹     this could be a problem normally, as long as local $_ is used in subs it should be ok. To doubly protect $wd, not only is the first method (passing a copy of path($wd) a new ref)                   â”‹
#â”‹     used, but also, in dosort, local is added to prevent any changing to $_, which would of changed the value of $wd to whatever sort method is used, in most cases, 'size'.                             â”‹
