#â”‹ #42 re: shortcircuit by way of $nocoremode (allows, disallows, or forces use of --core-mode, or '-c-' for short):                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹           a command to switch to coreutils' ls(1), all other arguments are sent to the new target                                                                                                        â”‹
#â”‹           (will fail if ls cannot be located) also added, for admins, $nocoremode, to prevent users from accessing coreutils version                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹           added another value to nocoremode, 2, to prevent use of lsx and always go to core mode, without the argument to do so                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹           added die when nocoremode is not 0, 1 or 2                                                                                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹           added optional alternate -core (derived from original --core-mode)                                                                                                                             â”‹
#â”‹           changed shorthand '-core' to '-c-' which is less toxic                                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹           added a value table below.                                                                                                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹           ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹           value of $nocoremode   effect                                                                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹           ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹               0                   use this program, allows use of --core-mode option which will cause /bin/ls to be run instead                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹               1                   use this program, never allow use of --core-mode at all                                                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹               2                   use (and pass all flags/args) to /bin/ls, except --core-mode (removes it if present)                                                                                   â”‹
#â”‹               other value         any other value than ones have undefined behavior, do not use them                                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹           ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹            again, stressing that $nocoremode is NOT set by --core-mode, it is set by YOU the developer and only alters the way                                                                           â”‹
#â”‹            regular users could interact with the --core-mode and execution of ls(2) even without --core-mode                                                                                             â”‹
#â”‹           ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------                                                                          â”‹
# THIS SECTION IS NEW AND NOT ENCASED YET
#  #43      Moved this experimental comment to this section as a 'new' item to contain CSCS compliance
            #########
            # (also, if userset columns, dont do it obviously they already specified what is wanted)
            # use column width to calculate how many columns can be shown; 4 is padding for the space at: 1) startofline 2) startofentry 3) endofentry 4) endofline (todo: make them dynamic?)
            #
            # compensate
            #
            # let it be stressed that this value should NEVER be anything other than 1 or 2!!!! (1=disabled 2=compensate)
            # however, i built in safety check just in case someone makes a no-no mistake here!
            # more info: compensate is an imaginary dimension, should be 1 but if it is way overwidth, set it to 2 (but never to 0!)
# #45       setfg/bg are  TEMPORARY, REMOVING VERY SOON in favor of Term::Put

#â”‹ #43                                                                                                                                                                                                      â”‹
#â”‹ #44 experimental during self-inflicted process: check /proc to ensure its not taintable on us                                                                                                            â”‹
#â”‹ #45                                                                                                                                                                                                      â”‹
#â”‹ #46                                                                                                                                                                                                      â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”£â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”«
#â”‹  FIRST SUBCLASSED OBJECT FOR SETTINGS USAGE                                                                                                                                                              â”‹
#â”£â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”«
#â”‹  (this is a bit long, but I appologize to no one!)                                                                                                                                                       â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹     The program has grown to the point where options on the command line, environment variable(s), a possible future rcfile, and the actual                                                              â”‹
#â”‹     effective settings, the settings themselves that are actually enabled need to be separated into a concrete object. This is due to overlapping and                                                    â”‹
#â”‹     overriding behaviors of the previously mentioned items (further referred to as the "setters"). Due to this (intentional) behavior, which is a                                                        â”‹
#â”‹     feature expected of *nix and BSD applications that run under a command line, there must now be implemented such an object.                                                                           â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹   SUBCLASSING                                                                                                                                                                                            â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹      This will be the first subclassed object relying on Tie variables and possibly Moose as well. [the following is stated prior to its creation:] The object is                                        â”‹
#â”‹     needed because the setters will be constantly changing the state of the program, and the program should not be expected to check all the setters                                                     â”‹
#â”‹     each time a setting's value is needed. Even a single setter can have contradicting arguments that toggle a setting on and back off again, in                                                         â”‹
#â”‹     the user's expected manner of doing so. A good example of this is the -A (--almost-all) and the -4 (--no-hidden) which are the reverse of each                                                       â”‹
#â”‹     other.                                                                                                                                                                                               â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹  WHY ARE THE ALTERNATIVES IGNORED?                                                                                                                                                                       â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹       I could have gone with using '+A' which would require a different getopt since G:L:D does not support that[1], but it wouldnt solve the                                                            â”‹
#â”‹     problem introduced by MINI_CMD_LS="-A" being present as well (or a future 'almost-all=1' in an rcfile, these cannot be checked at every point                                                        â”‹
#â”‹     in a reasonable way: if x == y do z is ok, but it becomes 'if h == i OR j == k OR l == m OR n == o ...... x == y do z, which is unacceptable                                                         â”‹
#â”‹     especially with hundreds of options DURING operation to be checked. Instead, all options are applied at start-up, and then stay the same                                                             â”‹
#â”‹     throughout the operation, and instead we get if stable_constant_object.x == y do z. Much better. Now, to further fixup performance, there might                                                      â”‹
#â”‹     be one more thing added; yes im talking about SHA checking of settings files and states. If they grow big and they will, SHASUMs will be used                                                        â”‹
#â”‹     before anything is even processed, if the SHAs match, we can just use the same cached settings for a resonable performance boost (any boost                                                          â”‹
#â”‹     that has no actual repercussions is a good boost and worth checksumming). This also allows for a degree of error correction that can be easily                                                       â”‹
#â”‹     implemented.                                                                                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹     [1] Getopt::Long (sorta) supports it though, though not simply enough and nowhere near enough to be a central object for options                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹         (this would add an extra call to Getopt::Long::Getoptions, with passthrough enabled)                                                                                                             â”‹
#â”‹     [2] Getopt::* the options are in fact writable, via dereferencing the hash but that is iffy and error prone, an object will be simpler                                                               â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ end of embedded notes section                                                                                                                                                                            â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ "sub" Side Notes                                                                                                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹       seta: name=seta, args=color(val) part=bg|rst|fg  exits=4                                                                                                                                           â”‹
#â”‹       seta: inf. wraparound to 1 (not 0) of values (-1(255),0(0),1(1),2(2)...255(255),256(1),257(2), etc)                                                                                                â”‹
#â”‹       termio: safe, sanitized by setup_termio_bin, @_ should never have slashes however                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹       colorize: if>for>given>when>line2>$num=$_item warning, do NOT convert to integer, this would destroy any padding of zeros needed to create 6c or 4c codes                                          â”‹
#â”‹                 $num: a number, always a color code (inline numbers wont get isolated like this)                                                                                                         â”‹
#â”‹                 last inner-inner: just text, add without discrimination (empty strings wont add anything, naturally)                                                                                     â”‹
#â”‹                 outer-most if, else: only one item, does not qualify to be interpreted as a color code (just give back same string)                                                                      â”‹
#â”£â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”«
#â”‹ REF SECTION/CHECKLIST                                                                                                                                                                                    â”‹
#â”£â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”«
#â”‹                                                                                                                                                                                                          â”‹
#â”‹ adding all these to this program, plus some of my own. avoid conflicts however by making sure none of my commands override the original                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹ note the output style WILL be different, if this is not ok then just use regular ls(1)!                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹ CHANGE:                                                                                                                                                                                                  â”‹
#â”‹ no longer going to be cloning options exactly, this is more of a guide now than a rule, with the introduction of some very different features, this                                                      â”‹
#â”‹ list program has taken me in a new direction which will have to say goodbye to the original thought to 'build on top of' the ls way of doing things                                                      â”‹
#â”‹ as before, you can use ls(1) instead if you dont like it. sorry!                                                                                                                                         â”‹
